114
00:14:30,960 --> 00:14:33,030
- I'm not responsible, Sam.
- Oh, no.

115
00:14:33,200 --> 00:14:35,032
- I told them how dangerous he was.
- You couldn't have.

116
00:14:35,200 --> 00:14:38,192
Two roadblocks and an all points
bulletin wouldn't stop a five-year-old.

117
00:14:38,334 --> 00:14:39,695
Well, he was your patient, Doctor.

118
00:14:39,720 --> 00:14:41,312
If precautions weren't strong enough,
you should have told somebody.

119
00:14:41,519 --> 00:14:43,591
I told everybody!
Nobody listened.

120
00:14:43,735 --> 00:14:44,934
There's nothing else I can do.

121
00:14:44,960 --> 00:14:46,711
You can get back in there
and get back on that telephone

122
00:14:46,879 --> 00:14:48,711
and tell them exactly
who walked out of here last night

123
00:14:48,879 --> 00:14:50,438
and tell them exactly
where he's going.

124
00:14:50,600 --> 00:14:52,591
- Probably going.
- I'm wasting my time.

125
00:14:52,759 --> 00:14:54,797
Sam, Haddonfield
is 150 miles away from here.

126
00:14:54,960 --> 00:14:56,600
Now, for God's sake,
he can't drive a car.

127
00:14:56,759 --> 00:14:58,398
He was doing
very well last night.

128
00:14:58,559 --> 00:15:01,073
Maybe someone around here
gave him lessons.

129
00:15:02,559 --> 00:15:04,437
( Car starts )

130
00:15:04,600 --> 00:15:07,399
(woman speaking
over loudspeaker )

131
00:15:13,399 --> 00:15:15,960
Teacher: And the book ends.

132
00:15:16,120 --> 00:15:20,239
But what Samuels
is really talking about here

133
00:15:20,440 --> 00:15:23,192
is fate.

134
00:15:23,399 --> 00:15:25,515
You see, fate

135
00:15:25,679 --> 00:15:28,513
caught up with
several lives here.

136
00:15:29,639 --> 00:15:33,349
No matter what course of action
Collins took,

137
00:15:33,519 --> 00:15:37,115
he was destined to his own fate.

138
00:15:37,279 --> 00:15:41,318
His own day of reckoning
with himself.

139
00:15:41,480 --> 00:15:44,597
The idea is

140
00:15:44,759 --> 00:15:48,115
that destiny is a very real,

141
00:15:48,279 --> 00:15:52,591
concrete thing that every person
has to deal with.

142
00:15:52,799 --> 00:15:55,474
How does Samuels view of fate

143
00:15:55,679 --> 00:15:58,638
differ from that of Costaine's?
Laufie?

144
00:15:58,799 --> 00:16:00,836
- Ma'am?
- Answer the question.

145
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:04,038
Oh, um,
Costaine wrote that fate

146
00:16:04,200 --> 00:16:06,076
was somehow related
only to religion,

147
00:16:06,240 --> 00:16:10,073
whereas Samuels felt that fate
was like a natural element

148
00:16:10,279 --> 00:16:12,032
like earth, air, fire, and water.

149
00:16:12,240 --> 00:16:15,789
That's right.
Samuels definitely personified fate.

150
00:16:15,960 --> 00:16:18,793
In Samuels' writing,
fate is immovable

151
00:16:18,960 --> 00:16:20,188
like a mountain.

152
00:16:20,360 --> 00:16:23,113
It stands where man
passes away.

153
00:16:23,279 --> 00:16:25,509
Fate never changes.

154
00:16:25,679 --> 00:16:27,909
- ( School bell ringing )
- ( Children shouting )

155
